Encryption at rest for objects.

Since early twenty-twenty-three, every new object is encrypted by default with keys AWS manages, no configuration needed. You override that only when you need stronger guarantees about the keys.

The default option uses opaque AWS-managed keys, a sensible baseline. The key-management-service option uses your own customer key, which gives you an audit trail, since every decryption is a logged ay-pee-eye call, plus per-key access control and rotation; the catch is that those calls are billable and rate-limited, which bucket keys mitigate by caching a bucket-level data key and cutting calls by about ninety-nine percent. A customer-provided-key option means you send the key with every request and AWS never stores it. And client-side encryption means you encrypt before upload, so AWS only ever sees ciphertext.

For regulated data, the key-management-service option is usually the right answer. For traffic in transit, enforce secure transport with a bucket policy that denies any non-secure request.
